There are some low-density lipoprotein-receptor-related proteins (LRP-1 and LRP-2) which can be utilized as drug carriers by endocytosis, initiating numerous signal pathways, and decomposition of proteins (Fig. 6
                     ). Although the transcytosis mechanism of nanoparticles through BBB is not clearly found yet. One probable mechanism might be the capability of surfactant-fabricated nanoparticles to absorb apolipoproteins (such as B and E) from the systemic circulation and employ LRP to cross the brain parenchyma through transcytosis process (Thomas et al., 2009). PLGA NPs are biodegradable and biocompatible nanocarriers for sustained and slow drug delivery. The polymer is well explored in multiple literature and commercial products are available in the market. Therefore, Pahuja et al., fabricated PLGA NPs ferrying dopamine (DA) for sustained and slow delivery across BBB to control PD and reversing neurochemical and behavioural deficits. Authors reported slow and constant DA release in systemic circulation, reduced plasma clearance, mitigated quinone adduct production, and reduced DA auto-oxidation-mediated toxicity in rat model. Notably, DA-NPs were efficiently internalized with dopaminergic SH-SY5Y cells and DA neuron in the substantia nigra and striatum after intravenous administration in 6-hydroxydopamine induced rat. Moreover, high level of DA and its metabolites in plasma was achieved without causing any substantial abnormality in brain, normalized level of ROS generation, and dopaminergic neurodegeneration. There were no observed abnormality in heart rate, blood pressure, abrupt changes in brain and peripheral visceral organs. These were confirmed in fluorescence and transmission electron microscopy (TEM) wherein aggregation behaviour of the injected nanoparticles were inspected in the striatal section of brain after days of infusion (Fig. 7
                     ) (Pahuja et al., 2015). In Fig. 8
                     , authors illustrated various findings especially (a) in vivo uptake of the injected PLGA-NPs (4 h after injection) and their accumulation in the nigral region of rat brain, (b) percentage uptake, (c) TH-immunolabeled nigral section and western blot of rat brain after injection, and (d) TEM microphotograph revealing the ultra-structure of nigral region of rat brain after single or double infusion of DA loaded NPs (Pahuja et al., 2015; Titze-de-Almeida et al., 2019).
